Here's a simple JavaScript `debounce` function with an example of how to use it:

Debounce prevents a function from being called too often by delaying its execution until a certain amount of time has passed since the last time it was called.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeoutId;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeoutId);
    timeoutId = setTimeout(() => {
      func.apply(this, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example usage:
function search(query) {
  console.log(`Searching for: ${query}`);
}

const debouncedSearch = debounce(search, 300);

debouncedSearch("hello"); // This will be delayed by 300ms
debouncedSearch("world"); // This will cancel the previous call and start a new 300ms delay
```

In this example, the `debouncedSearch` function will only call the `search` function if there is a 300ms pause between calls. This is useful for scenarios like search input fields where you don't want to trigger a search on every keystroke.
